  "prompt": "What is covered and uncovered interest parity?",
  "response": "Interest parity refers to the relationship between interest rates, exchange rates, and expected returns on investments in different currencies. There are two main types of interest parity:\n\n1. Covered Interest Parity (CIP):\n- Assumes that investors use forward contracts to hedge against exchange rate risk\n- The return on a domestic investment should equal the return on a foreign investment after accounting for forward exchange rates\n- Eliminates potential arbitrage opportunities between domestic and foreign financial markets\n- Equation: (1 + i_domestic) = (1 + i_foreign) * (F/S)\n- Where:\n  * i_domestic = domestic interest rate\n  * i_foreign = foreign interest rate\n  * F = forward exchange rate\n  * S = spot exchange rate\n\n2. Uncovered Interest Parity (UIP):\n- Does not involve hedging exchange rate risk\n- Assumes investors are willing to accept exchange rate risk\n- Expected return on domestic and foreign investments should be equivalent\n- Equation: (1 + i_domestic) = (1 + i_foreign) * (E(S_t+1)/S)\n- Where:\n  * E(S_t+1) = expected future spot exchange rate\n  * S = current spot exchange rate\n\nKey differences:\n- CIP uses forward contracts for hedging\n- UIP involves speculation on future exchange rates\n- CIP typically holds more consistently in practice\n- UIP is more theoretical and often does not perfectly hold in real markets",
